  "points": [
    {
      "title": "Subject concords and the present (ndi-, u-, ba-…)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say who is doing what",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 1,
      "explanation": "Every verb starts with a subject concord: ndi- (I), u- (you / he-she cl.1), si- (we), ni- (you all), ba- (they). The long present adds -ya- when nothing follows the verb: Ndiyafunda (I am studying); with an object the -ya- drops: Ndifunda isiXhosa (I study Xhosa).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} isiXhosa.",
          "answer": "Ndifunda",
          "translation": "I study Xhosa.",
          "hint": "ndi- + funda (no -ya- before an object)",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}}.",
          "answer": "Ndiyafunda",
          "translation": "I am studying.",
          "hint": "long present with -ya-",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Noun classes 1/2: um-/aba- (people)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Talk about people, one or many",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 2,
      "explanation": "Xhosa nouns carry class prefixes. Class 1/2 is people: umntu/abantu (person/people), umfundi/abafundi (student/s), umntwana/abantwana (child/ren). The class drives agreement on everything that follows.",
      "culture_note": "The class system (about 15 classes) is the engine of the whole language — one class pair at a time is the way in.",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Bantu noun classes",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noun_class#Bantu_languages"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Umfundi omnye, {{answer}} ababini.",
          "answer": "abafundi",
          "translation": "One student, two students.",
          "hint": "aba- plural",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} uyafunda.",
          "answer": "Umntwana",
          "translation": "The child is studying.",
          "hint": "um- singular (class 1)",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Noun classes 5/6 and 7/8",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Use the ili-/ama- and isi-/izi- families",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 3,
      "explanation": "Class 5/6: i(li)-/ama- — ilizwe/amazwe (country/ies), iqanda/amaqanda (egg/s). Class 7/8: isi-/izi- — isitya/izitya (dish/es); isi- also names languages: isiXhosa, isiNgesi (English).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Bantu noun classes",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noun_class#Bantu_languages"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Iqanda elinye, {{answer}} amabini.",
          "answer": "amaqanda",
          "translation": "One egg, two eggs.",
          "hint": "ama- plural (class 6)",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Ndithetha {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "isiXhosa",
          "translation": "I speak Xhosa.",
          "hint": "isi- language noun",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Noun classes 9/10: in-/izin-",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Use the in-/izin- family",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 4,
      "explanation": "Class 9/10 covers many everyday nouns and animals: inja/izinja (dog/s), indlu/izindlu (house/s), incwadi/iincwadi (book/s — long ii- plural). Their agreements use i-/zi-: Inja iyatya (The dog is eating), Izinja ziyatya.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Bantu noun classes",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noun_class#Bantu_languages"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Inja enye, {{answer}} ezimbini.",
          "answer": "izinja",
          "translation": "One dog, two dogs.",
          "hint": "izin- plural",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Incwadi enye, {{answer}} ezimbini.",
          "answer": "iincwadi",
          "translation": "One book, two books.",
          "hint": "long ii- plural",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Identifying copulatives (ngu-, yi-)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say 'it is …'",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 5,
      "explanation": "'It is X' prefixes the noun: ngu- for class 1/1a (people/names) — NguThemba (It's Themba), ngumfundi (he's a student); yi- for class 9 — yincwadi (it's a book); li-, si-, etc. for other classes. Negation prefixes asi-: asingumfundi (he is not a student).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} lo.",
          "answer": "NguThemba",
          "translation": "This is Themba.",
          "hint": "ngu- + name",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} le.",
          "answer": "Yincwadi",
          "translation": "This is a book.",
          "hint": "yi- + class-9 noun",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Present negative (andi-…-i)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say what is not happening",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 6,
      "explanation": "Wrap the verb in a negative concord and final -i: ndiyafunda → andifundi (I don't study), uyafuna → akafuni (he doesn't want — u- becomes aka-), bayasebenza → abasebenzi (they don't work).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} isiNgesi.",
          "answer": "Andithethi",
          "translation": "I don't speak English.",
          "hint": "andi- + thetha + -i",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} ukutya.",
          "answer": "Akafuni",
          "translation": "He/she doesn't want food.",
          "hint": "aka- + funa + -i",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Locatives (e-…-ini)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say where things happen",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 7,
      "explanation": "Places are made with e- (and often -ini): isikolo → esikolweni (at school), indlu → endlwini (in the house), iKapa → eKapa (in Cape Town). Ndihlala eKapa (I live in Cape Town), Ndiya esikolweni (I'm going to school).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Ndihlala {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "eKapa",
          "translation": "I live in Cape Town.",
          "hint": "e- + place name",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Abantwana bafunda {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "esikolweni",
          "translation": "The children study at school.",
          "hint": "e- + isikolo + -ini",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Questions (ntoni, bani, phi)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Ask what, who, and where",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 8,
      "explanation": "Question words follow the verb: Ufuna ntoni? (What do you want?), Ngubani igama lakho? (What/who is your name?), Uhlala phi? (Where do you live?). Yes/no questions just use rising intonation, or open with Ingaba: Ingaba uyeza? (Are you coming?).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Ufuna {{answer}}?",
          "answer": "ntoni",
          "translation": "What do you want?",
          "hint": "'what' after the verb",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Uhlala {{answer}}?",
          "answer": "phi",
          "translation": "Where do you live?",
          "hint": "'where' after the verb",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
