      "explanation": "'Have' fuses -na- with the noun: ndi + na + incwadi → Ndinencwadi (I have a book), Unemali (you have / she has money), Banabantwana (they have children). Negative: Andinamali (I have no money).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}}.",
          "answer": "Ndinencwadi",
          "translation": "I have a book.",
          "hint": "ndi + na + incwadi fused",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}}.",
          "answer": "Andinamali",
          "translation": "I have no money.",
          "hint": "negative: a- + ndi + na + imali",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Possessive concords (yam, wam, bam…)",
      "level": "A2",
      "function": "Say whose something is",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 1,
      "explanation": "The possessive agrees with the THING possessed: incwadi yam (my book, cl.9 ya-), umntwana wam (my child, cl.1 wa-), isitya sam (my dish, cl.7 sa-), abantwana bam (my children, cl.2 ba-). The endings -m (my), -kho (your), -khe (his/her) stay constant.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Incwadi {{answer}} ilahlekile.",
          "answer": "yam",
          "translation": "My book is lost.",
          "hint": "class-9 possessive + 'my'",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Umntwana {{answer}} uyafunda.",
          "answer": "wakhe",
          "translation": "Her child is studying.",
          "hint": "class-1 possessive + 'her'",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Recent past (-ile)",
      "level": "A2",
      "function": "Say what (has) happened",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 2,
      "explanation": "The recent past ends in -ile when the verb closes the clause: Ndifundile (I studied / have studied), Bafikile (They have arrived). Before an object the short form -e is used: Ndibone umfundi? — commonly Ndibonile in isolation; keep -ile clause-final at this level.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}}.",
          "answer": "Ndifundile",
          "translation": "I have studied.",
          "hint": "recent past -ile",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "Abantwana {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "bafikile",
          "translation": "The children have arrived.",
          "hint": "ba- + fika + -ile",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Future (-za ku-)",
      "level": "A2",
      "function": "Say what will happen",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 3,
      "explanation": "The future combines -za (come) with the infinitive: Ndiza kufunda (I will study), Uza kufika ngomso (She will arrive tomorrow), Siza kuthetha (We will talk). Colloquially it contracts (ndizo-/ndizaku-).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Ndiza {{answer}} ngomso.",
          "answer": "kufunda",
          "translation": "I will study tomorrow.",
          "hint": "ku- infinitive after -za",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} kufika ngomso.",
          "answer": "Uza",
          "translation": "He/she will arrive tomorrow.",
          "hint": "u- + -za",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Object concords",
      "level": "A2",
      "function": "Point the verb at its object",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 4,
      "explanation": "The object can live inside the verb as a concord before the stem: Ndiyayifunda (incwadi) — I am reading it (the book, cl.9 -yi-); Ndiyambona (umntu) — I see him (cl.1 -m-); Ndiyazithanda (izinja) — I love them (cl.10 -zi-).",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Xhosa language — grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language#Grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "Incwadi? {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "Ndiyayifunda",
          "translation": "The book? I am reading it.",
          "hint": "object -yi- (class 9) inside the verb",
          "display_order": 1
        },
        {
          "sentence": "UThemba? {{answer}}.",
          "answer": "Ndiyambona",
          "translation": "Themba? I see him.",
          "hint": "object -m- (class 1) inside the verb",
          "display_order": 2
        }
      ]
    },
